Ian Badcoe wrote:

&gt;At 22:36 23/08/2004, Colin wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;Ken Wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;But the idea of only adding a % of excess and disjoint genes I am
&gt;&gt;&gt;unsure about.  If a complex of genes has formed that are all
&gt;&gt;&gt;interdependent, that could be a bad move.  Maybe safer would be to
&gt;&gt;&gt;just make adding *all* the excess and disjoint genes probabilistic.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Good point.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Or, does that imply that the two individuals are too different to breed 
&gt;successfully anyway?
&gt;  
&gt;
I suppose It&#39;s true to say that that most pairs of genomes selected for 
crossover will be in the same species and will therefore be very 
similar, so in actual fact you might not encounter very many disjoint an 
excess genes. Two exceptions to this, (1) A small proportion of 
inter-species mating is sometimes used in NEAT (say 1%). (2) If you use 
a dynamic speciation threshold then the difference between genomes in a 
given species increases as complexity of the population rises, this is 
in order to keep the number of species down.  This second point may be 
less of an issuse with phased searching, but complexity can still rise 
if that is where the good solutions are to be found.

&gt;If you had a set of genes which were all in one parent, mutually 
&gt;interdependent, and beneficial, could that be a definition of a &quot;module&quot;?
&gt;  
&gt;
Yes, I would say so.

&gt;I guess nature gets around this as follows:
&gt;
&gt;- when new genes first appear they are exchanged between individuals so 
&gt;similar that they tend to get the same support framework from both parents.
&gt;
&gt;- as mutual interdependence between genes grows (over very long periods) 
&gt;the genes tend to get shuffled close together so that they do crossover as 
&gt;a single unit
&gt;  
&gt;
hmm, so genes that are close together tend to be functionaly dependent. 
Genotype proximity indicates phenotype proximity. Whereas in NEAT the 
genes always remain in the order they were added to the genome (this 
makes comparison nice and fast), but perhaps we are loosing some 
important properties by doing this - namely, crossover could be allowed 
to re-arrange genes into functionaly dependent groups. Hey I like this 
idea a lot Ian.

Colin.
